  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I distinguish between different ranks of the Indian army?",
  "response": "The Indian Army has a well-structured hierarchy of ranks, similar to other armies around the world. Here's a brief overview of the ranks in the Indian Army, starting from the lowest to the highest:\n\n1. **Sepoy**: This is the entry-level rank in the Indian Army. It is equivalent to a private in other armies.\n\n2. **Lance Naik**: This is the first promotion a sepoy can receive. It is equivalent to a lance corporal in other armies.\n\n3. **Naik**: This rank is equivalent to a corporal in other armies. A Naik is typically in charge of a section of soldiers.\n\n4. **Havildar**: This rank is equivalent to a sergeant in other armies. Havildars are usually section commanders.\n\n5. **Naib Subedar**: This is the first rank in the Junior Commissioned Officer (JCO) category. Naib Subedars are equivalent to a warrant officer in other armies.\n\n6. **Subedar**: This rank is also in the JCO category and is equivalent to a senior warrant officer in other armies.\n\n7. **Subedar Major**: This is the highest rank in the JCO category. Subedar Majors are equivalent to a master warrant officer in other armies.\n\n8. **Lieutenant**: This is the entry-level rank for commissioned officers. Lieutenants are usually platoon commanders.\n\n9. **Captain**: This rank is typically held by company second-in-commands or by officers commanding independent platoons.\n\n10. **Major**: Majors are usually company commanders or serve as staff officers.\n\n11. **Lieutenant Colonel**: This rank is typically held by battalion second-in-commands or by officers commanding independent companies.\n\n12. **Colonel**: Colonels are typically battalion commanders or serve as staff officers at higher headquarters.\n\n13. **Brigadier**: This is the first general officer rank. Brigadiers typically command brigades or serve as staff officers at higher headquarters.\n\n14. **Major General**: Major Generals typically command divisions or serve as staff officers at higher headquarters.\n\n15. **Lieutenant General**: Lieutenant Generals typically command corps or serve as staff officers at higher headquarters.\n\n16. **General**: This is the highest rank in the Indian Army. The General serves as the Chief of Army Staff (COAS), the professional head of the Indian Army.\n\nIn addition to these ranks, there are also honorary ranks such as Field Marshal, which has been awarded to only two officers in the history of the Indian Army.\n\nYou can distinguish between the different ranks of the Indian Army by their insignia, which are typically worn on the shoulders or chest of the uniform. The insignia for each rank is unique and can be easily identified.",
